You can have a key to hold the counter and use [`INCR`](https://redis.io/commands/INCR) command to change counter value. This command returns the counter value after operation is performed.

You can use `ValueOperations` in Spring Data Redis to issue this command. Here&#39;s sample code:

```java
StringRedisTemplate rt = new StringRedisTemplate(factory);

ValueOperations&lt;String, String&gt; valueOps = rt.opsForValue();

valueOps.set(KEY, &quot;10&quot;);
System.out.println(valueOps.get(key));
System.out.println(valueOps.increment(KEY, 1));
System.out.println(valueOps.increment(KEY, 1));
System.out.println(valueOps.increment(KEY, -1));
```

The output will be:
```
10
11
12
11
```


In case you have many counters to maintain you can store them in a `hashmap` and use [`HINCRBY`](https://redis.io/commands/HINCRBY) command. With Spring Data Redis you can use [`HashOperations`](https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/redis/docs/current/api/org/springframework/data/redis/core/HashOperations.html) to manipulate values in the hash. [See this page](https://stackabuse.com/spring-boot-with-redis-hashoperations-crud-functionality/) for more detailed explanation.

