@kelalaka You used RSA in your example. Is it ok to use two symmetric encryption ? 
User gives a password. The program apply Argon2 and store the result in DB. A KEK (let&#39;s say a key for AES) is generated based on the clear password. A DEK (AES as well) is generated randomly, and encrypted by the KEK. We use the clear DEK while the program is running and data need to be stored/read. 
When the user wants to use the program again, he needs to input his password, the program check if its hash matches the saved hash. If it does, we apply the function to obtain the KEK and we can decrypt DEK.

