```java
public class UpdateAnchorsInArScene {

  private MyRepository myRepository;

  public UpdateAnchorsInArScene(MyRepository myRepository) {
    this.myRepository = myRepository;
  }
  
  public void update(Anchor anchor) {
    myRepository.updateAnchorsInArScene(anchor);
  }
}
```
Then, in order to obtain an instance of `UpdateAnchorsInArScene`, you can use [Dependency Injection][1] (recommended) or just manually do it. In case you don&#39;t understand why I separated into a `Repository` and an `Implementation` instead of an all-in-one, it&#39;s because, this way, you can make a fake implementation for testing and just change the argument you pass in to `UpdateAnchorsInArScene` later.
```java
final UpdateAnchorsInArScene updateAnchors = new UpdateAnchorsInArScene(new MyRepositoryImpl());
updateAnchors.update(anchor);
```
Finally, you can just pass that `UpdateAnchorsInArScene` instance to achieve what you want.


[1]: https://developer.android.com/training/dependency-injection/hilt-android

